<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><a href="//www.slideshare.net/CFCC15/indias-energy-and-climate-debate-uncertainties-in-future-emissions-and-the-scope-for-cobenefits">Indiaâs Energy and Climate Debate: Uncertainties in Future Emissions and the Scope for Co-benefits</a></p></blockquote>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">AÂ <a href="https://www.twitter.com/sbiville/status/619515525648003072">photo tweeted by Sylvaine Biville</a>, who was managing communications at the meeting, captures my own desperation in trying to get from one overflowing session (I&#8217;m pretty sure it was &#8220;<a href="//cfcc.event.y-congress.com/ScientificProcess/Schedule/index.html?setLng=en#filters=[{&quot;name&quot;:&quot;fulltext&quot;,&quot;values&quot;:[&quot;betts&quot;]}]">A world above 2Â°C global warming: understanding risks and developing transformative solutions</a>&#8220;) to another.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">A great moment, reflecting the inevitability of diverse responses to climate risk on a variegated planet, came during a plenary panel focused on ways to satisfy fast-growing human energy needs while moving away from burning fossil fuels, which remain the world&#8217;s dominant energy source.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Participants from China and Europe demonstrated how a mix of orientations and approaches is inevitable, and a positive thing.</p>
<div class="w480">
<div class="w480 youtube-video-container">
<div class="youtube-video" data-youtube-id="qh1qTWv-NsY" data-start="">
